<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Full detailed requirements</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>High-level scope only</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Flexibility</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Rigid</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Flexible to change</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Deliverables</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Complete SRS document</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Vision document, initial use cases</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Approach</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Linear</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Iterative &amp; exploratory</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A1 <strong>Tip:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Waterfall</strong> is great for <strong>stable, well-understood =
projects</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Inception Phase</strong> is part of <strong>iterative developmen=
t</strong>, ideal for projects with <strong>uncertain requirements</strong>=
.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>If you want, I can <strong>draw a diagram comparing Waterfall life cycle=
 with Iterative life cycle showing the Inception phase</strong> for better =
clarity.</p>
<p>Do you want me to do that?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"7">
<li>
<p>UML diagrams, Interaction and Collaboration Diagram for designing Softwa=
re.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Excellent =F0=9F=91=8C Let=E2=80=99s go through <strong>UML diagrams</st=
rong> first, then focus on <strong>Interaction Diagrams</strong> (Sequence =
+ Collaboration) used in designing software.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8C1.UMLDi=
agramsOverview">=F0=9F=93=8C 1. UML Diagrams Overview</h1>
<p><strong>UML (Unified Modeling Language)</strong> provides a <strong>stan=
dard way to visualize the design of a system</strong>.<br>
There are <strong>14 UML diagrams</strong>, classified into <strong>Structu=
ral</strong> and <strong>Behavioral</strong>:</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=E2=9C=85Structural=
Diagrams(whatthesystemis):">=E2=9C=85 <strong>Structural Diagrams</strong> =
(what the system <em>is</em>):</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Class Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 shows classes &amp; relationshi=
ps</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Object Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 instances of classes at runtim=
e</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Component Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 software components/modules=
</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Deployment Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 physical deployment of sof=
tware on hardware</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Package Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 organization of packages</p><=
/li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=E2=9C=85Behavioral=
Diagrams(howthesystembehaves):">=E2=9C=85 <strong>Behavioral Diagrams</stro=
ng> (how the system <em>behaves</em>):</h3>
<ol start=3D"6">
<li>
<p><strong>Use Case Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 interactions between actors =
&amp; system</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Sequence Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 order of messages over time<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Collaboration (Communication) Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 object =
interactions with focus on relationships</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Activity Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 workflow or processes</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>State Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 states and transitions of objec=
ts</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Interaction Overview Diagram</strong> =E2=80=93 high-level inter=
actions</p></li>
</ol>
<p><em>(Other specialized ones: Timing, Profile, Composite Structure)</em><=
/p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8C2.Inter=
actionDiagrams">=F0=9F=93=8C 2. Interaction Diagrams</h1>
<p>Interaction Diagrams are part of <strong>behavioral UML diagrams</strong=
>, and they show how <strong>objects collaborate</strong> to fulfill a beha=
vior.<br>
There are two main types:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9A.Seque=
nceDiagram">=F0=9F=94=B9 A. <strong>Sequence Diagram</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Shows <strong>time-ordered interactions</strong> between objects.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>Focus =3D <em>time sequence of messages</em>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Vertical axis =3D time, Horizontal =3D objects.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-Example:OnlineShopp=
ing=E2=80=93PlaceOrder">Example: <strong>Online Shopping =E2=80=93 Place Or=
der</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Custome=
r    Cart    Order    PaymentSystem
   |          |       |          |
   |---selectProduct()----------&gt;|
   |---addToCart()---&gt;|          |
   |---checkout()---------------&gt;|
   |                  |---makePayment()--&gt;|
   |                  |&lt;--paymentStatus() |
   |&lt;--orderConfirmed()-------------------|
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9E=A1 Helps us see <strong>step-by-step interactions over time</stro=
ng>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9B.Colla=
boration(Communication)Diagram">=F0=9F=94=B9 B. <strong>Collaboration (Comm=
unication) Diagram</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Shows <strong>structural relationships</strong> between objects and the =
<strong>messages exchanged</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Focus =3D <em>links between objects</em>, not timeline.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Messages are numbered to show order.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-Example:PlaceOrderC=
ollaborationDiagram">Example: <strong>Place Order Collaboration Diagram</st=
rong></h3>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">[Custom=
er]=20
   1: selectProduct()=20
   2: addToCart()
   3: checkout()
     |
     v
[Cart] ---4: createOrder()---&gt; [Order]
                      |
                      v
                  5: makePayment()
                      |
                      v
                [PaymentSystem]
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9E=A1 Helps us see <strong>which objects interact and in what sequen=
ce</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8C3.Whent=
oUseWhich?">=F0=9F=93=8C 3. When to Use Which?</h1>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Sequence Diagram</strong> =E2=86=92 When order of messages matte=
rs (timeline focus).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Collaboration Diagram</strong> =E2=86=92 When relationships betw=
een objects matter (structural focus).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8C4.JavaE=
xample(MappingUML=E2=86=92Code)">=F0=9F=93=8C 4. Java Example (Mapping UML =
=E2=86=92 Code)</h1>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
ustomer {
    Cart cart =3D new Cart();

    void placeOrder() {
        cart.addProduct(new Product("Laptop", 1200));
        Order order =3D cart.createOrder();
        order.makePayment(new Payment("CreditCard", 1200));
    }
}

class Cart {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products =3D new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    void addProduct(Product p) {
        products.add(p);
    }

    Order createOrder() {
        return new Order(products);
    }
}

class Order {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products;
    Payment payment;

    Order(List&lt;Product&gt; products) {
        this.products =3D products;
    }

    void makePayment(Payment p) {
        this.payment =3D p;
        System.out.println("Payment done via " + p.method);
    }
}

class Product {
    String name;
    double price;
    Product(String n, double p) { name =3D n; price =3D p; }
}

class Payment {
    String method;
    double amount;
    Payment(String m, double a) { method =3D m; amount =3D a; }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Summary</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>UML Diagrams</strong> =E2=86=92 14 standard diagrams (structural=
 + behavioral).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Interaction Diagrams</strong> =E2=86=92 Sequence (time focus) &a=
mp; Collaboration (relationship focus).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Both used together in <strong>software design</strong> to model dynamic =
behavior.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Do you want me to <strong>draw a proper UML Sequence &amp; =
Collaboration diagram</strong> for the "Place Order" example (with actors, =
classes, and messages), so you can visualize them side by side?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"8">
<li>
<p>Designing Objects with responsibilities.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Great question =F0=9F=91=8D Now we=E2=80=99re entering <strong>Object-Or=
iented Design (OOD)</strong> concepts.<br>
When designing software, one of the most important tasks is to assign <stro=
ng>responsibilities</strong> to objects (classes/instances).</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8CDesigni=
ngObjectswithResponsibilities">=F0=9F=93=8C Designing Objects with Responsi=
bilities</h1>
<p>In <strong>Object-Oriented Software Design</strong>,</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>An <strong>object</strong> =3D an entity that has <strong>state (attribu=
tes)</strong> + <strong>behavior (methods)</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Responsibility</strong> =3D what an object <em>knows</em> and <e=
m>what it does</em>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 So, the design process involves <strong>deciding which clas=
s should be responsible for which task</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.Types=
ofResponsibilities">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. Types of Responsibilities</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Knowing Responsibilities (Knowledge)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Objects know about themselves (attributes) and related objects.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <code>Student</code> object knows <code>name</code>, <code>id</code>, =
and which <code>Course</code> they are enrolled in.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Doing Responsibilities (Behavior)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Objects perform actions (methods).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <code>Payment</code> object processes a transaction.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.GRASP=
Principles(GeneralResponsibilityAssignmentSoftwarePatterns)">=F0=9F=94=B9 2=
. GRASP Principles (General Responsibility Assignment Software Patterns)</h=
2>
<p>When assigning responsibilities, we follow <strong>GRASP patterns</stron=
g>:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Information Expert</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Responsibility should be assigned to the class that has the information.=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: <code>Invoice</code> should calculate <code>total()</code> beca=
use it has all line items.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Creator</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A class that contains or aggregates another should be responsible for cr=
eating it.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: <code>Cart</code> creates an <code>Order</code>.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Controller</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Assign responsibility for handling system events to a controller class.<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: <code>OrderController</code> handles <code>placeOrder()</code>.=
</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Low Coupling &amp; High Cohesion</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Design should minimize dependencies (low coupling).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Each class should focus on a single purpose (high cohesion).</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.Examp=
le:OnlineShopping(ObjectResponsibilities)">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Example: Online =
Shopping (Object Responsibilities)</h2>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-ClassesandResponsib=
ilities:">Classes and Responsibilities:</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Customer</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Knows: name, email, cart</p></li>
<li>
<p>Does: add items to cart, checkout</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Cart</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Knows: list of products</p></li>
<li>
<p>Does: calculate total, create order</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Order</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Knows: orderID, products, payment</p></li>
<li>
<p>Does: confirm order, generate invoice</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Payment</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Knows: payment type, amount</p></li>
<li>
<p>Does: process transaction</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.JavaE=
xample">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. Java Example</h2>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
ustomer {
    String name;
    String email;
    Cart cart =3D new Cart();

    void checkout() {
        Order order =3D cart.createOrder();
        order.makePayment(new Payment("CreditCard", order.calculateTotal())=
);
    }
}

class Cart {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products =3D new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    void addProduct(Product p) {
        products.add(p);
    }

    double calculateTotal() {
        return products.stream().mapToDouble(p -&gt; p.price).sum();
    }

    Order createOrder() {
        return new Order(products);
    }
}

class Order {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products;
    Payment payment;

    Order(List&lt;Product&gt; products) {
        this.products =3D products;
    }

    double calculateTotal() {
        return products.stream().mapToDouble(p -&gt; p.price).sum();
    }

    void makePayment(Payment p) {
        this.payment =3D p;
        System.out.println("Payment done via " + p.method + " for $" + p.am=
ount);
    }
}

class Product {
    String name;
    double price;
    Product(String n, double p) { name =3D n; price =3D p; }
}

class Payment {
    String method;
    double amount;
    Payment(String m, double a) { method =3D m; amount =3D a; }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B95.Visua=
lization(ResponsibilitiesChart)">=F0=9F=94=B9 5. Visualization (Responsibil=
ities Chart)</h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"e5=
c91264-98ba-4dc3-b723-e56855c19117" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Class</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Knows</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Does</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Customer</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>name, email, cart</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>checkout(), addToCart()</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Cart</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>list of products</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>calculateTotal(), createOrder()</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Order</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>products, payment</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>makePayment(), calculateTotal()</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Payment</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>method, amount</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>process transaction</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Product</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>name, price</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>-</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Summary:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Designing objects with responsibilities =3D deciding <em>who knows what<=
/em> and <em>who does what</em>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>GRASP patterns help in distributing responsibilities properly.</p></li>
<li>
<p>This leads to <strong>low coupling, high cohesion, and maintainable syst=
ems</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Do you want me to also explain <strong>how to move from Use=
 Case =E2=86=92 Assigning Responsibilities (via UML Sequence &amp; Class Di=
agrams)</strong> so you see the <strong>full workflow</strong>?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"9">
<li>
<p>GRASP patterns with General Principles in assigning responsibilities: In=
formation expert, Creator, Low Coupling and High Cohesion, Creating design =
class diagrams and mapping design to codes.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8D now we=E2=80=99re going deep into <strong>GRASP Pat=
terns</strong> and how they help in assigning responsibilities during <stro=
ng>Object-Oriented Design</strong>. Let=E2=80=99s break it down step by ste=
p with principles, examples, and mapping to code.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8CGRASPPa=
tterns&amp;GeneralPrinciples">=F0=9F=93=8C GRASP Patterns &amp; General Pri=
nciples</h1>
<p><strong>GRASP (General Responsibility Assignment Software Patterns)</str=
ong> =3D Guidelines to assign responsibilities to objects in a way that lea=
ds to <strong>maintainable, reusable, and robust software</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.Infor=
mationExpert">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. Information Expert</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Principle:</strong> Assign responsibility to the cl=
ass that has the necessary information.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Invoice</code> should calculate <code>totalAmount()</code>, becaus=
e it knows its <code>LineItems</code>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Design Class Diagram:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Invoice=
 -----&gt; LineItem -----&gt; Product
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Java Code Example:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class P=
roduct {
    String name;
    double price;
    Product(String n, double p) { name =3D n; price =3D p; }
}

class LineItem {
    Product product;
    int quantity;
    LineItem(Product p, int q) { product =3D p; quantity =3D q; }
    double getSubTotal() { return product.price * quantity; }
}

class Invoice {
    List&lt;LineItem&gt; items =3D new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    void addItem(Product p, int q) {
        items.add(new LineItem(p, q));
    }

    double getTotal() {
        return items.stream().mapToDouble(LineItem::getSubTotal).sum();
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Here, <strong>Invoice</strong> is the Information Expert for c=
alculating the total.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.Creat=
or">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. Creator</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Principle:</strong> Assign responsibility to the cl=
ass that contains or aggregates another class to create instances of it.</p=
>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A <code>Cart</code> creates <code>Order</code> objects.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Design Class Diagram:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Custome=
r ---&gt; Cart ---&gt; Order
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Java Code Example:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
art {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products =3D new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    void addProduct(Product p) { products.add(p); }

    Order createOrder() {
        return new Order(products);
    }
}

class Order {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products;
    Order(List&lt;Product&gt; prods) { products =3D new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(p=
rods); }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Cart</strong> is the best place to create an <code>Ord=
er</code>, because it <em>owns</em> the products.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.LowCo=
upling">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Low Coupling</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Principle:</strong> Minimize dependencies between c=
lasses. This increases <strong>reusability and flexibility</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Bad Example:</strong><br>
If <code>Customer</code> directly accesses database logic, it creates stron=
g coupling.</p>
<p><strong>Better Example:</strong><br>
Introduce a <code>CustomerRepository</code> class that handles persistence.=
</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
ustomer {
    String name;
    Customer(String n) { name =3D n; }
}

class CustomerRepository {
    void save(Customer c) {
        System.out.println("Saving customer " + c.name);
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Now, <code>Customer</code> is <strong>not tightly coupled</str=
ong> to database logic.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.HighC=
ohesion">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. High Cohesion</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Principle:</strong> Each class should focus on a si=
ngle purpose, making it <strong>easier to maintain</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Bad Example:</strong><br>
A single <code>Customer</code> class that manages shopping, payment, and or=
der processing.</p>
<p><strong>Better Example (High Cohesion):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>Customer</code> =E2=86=92 only holds customer data.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Cart</code> =E2=86=92 manages products.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Payment</code> =E2=86=92 handles transactions.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>This keeps responsibilities clear and avoids "God classes."</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8C5.Creat=
ingDesignClassDiagrams(DCD)">=F0=9F=93=8C 5. Creating Design Class Diagrams=
 (DCD)</h1>
<p>A <strong>Design Class Diagram</strong> is an extension of UML Class Dia=
gram where we show responsibilities.</p>
<p><strong>Example for Online Shopping System:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">+------=
------------+          +----------------+
|   Customer       |          |   Product      |
|------------------|          |----------------|
| - name           |&lt;&gt;-------&gt;| - name         |
| - email          |          | - price        |
|------------------|          |----------------|
| + checkout()     |          |                |
+------------------+          +----------------+

       |
       v
+------------------+          +----------------+
|      Cart        |&lt;&gt;-------&gt;|   Order        |
|------------------|          |----------------|
| - products       |          | - products     |
|------------------|          | + confirm()    |
| + addProduct()   |          | + total()      |
| + createOrder()  |          |                |
+------------------+          +----------------+
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8C6.Mappi=
ngDesigntoCode">=F0=9F=93=8C 6. Mapping Design to Code</h1>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-UML=E2=86=92JavaImp=
lementation">UML =E2=86=92 Java Implementation</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Customer class (from DCD):</strong></p></li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
ustomer {
    String name, email;
    Cart cart =3D new Cart();

    void checkout() {
        Order order =3D cart.createOrder();
        System.out.println("Order confirmed with total: " + order.total());
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Cart class (responsibility: manage products, create order):</str=
ong></p></li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
art {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products =3D new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    void addProduct(Product p) { products.add(p); }

    Order createOrder() { return new Order(products); }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Order class (responsibility: confirm and calculate total):</stro=
ng></p></li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class O=
rder {
    List&lt;Product&gt; products;
    Order(List&lt;Product&gt; products) { this.products =3D products; }

    double total() {
        return products.stream().mapToDouble(p -&gt; p.price).sum();
    }

    void confirm() {
        System.out.println("Order confirmed. Total: " + total());
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 The <strong>DCD directly translates to classes, attributes, an=
d methods</strong> in Java.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8E=AFSummary=
">=F0=9F=8E=AF Summary</h1>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>GRASP patterns</strong> guide <em>who should do what</em>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Information Expert</strong> =E2=86=92 give tasks to the class wi=
th necessary data.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Creator</strong> =E2=86=92 let the container/aggregator create o=
bjects.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Low Coupling</strong> =E2=86=92 minimize dependencies.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>High Cohesion</strong> =E2=86=92 one class, one clear responsibi=
lity.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>DCDs (Design Class Diagrams)</strong> visualize these responsibi=
lities.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Mapping DCD =E2=86=92 Java code</strong> ensures clarity, mainta=
inability, and scalability.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Do you want me to also include <strong>other GRASP patterns=
 (like Controller, Polymorphism, Indirection, Pure Fabrication)</strong> wi=
th examples in Java, or focus only on these four for now?</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"10">
<li>
<p>Software Testing: White Box and Black Box testing. Basis Path Testing. T=
esting for specialized environment.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Got it =E2=9C=85 As a software engineer, let me give you a <strong>struc=
tured explanation</strong> of these testing concepts with examples where ne=
eded.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8CSoftwar=
eTesting">=F0=9F=93=8C Software Testing</h1>
<p>Software Testing is the process of <strong>evaluating software</strong> =
to ensure it meets requirements, works correctly, and is free from defects.=
<br>
Two main approaches are <strong>White Box Testing</strong> and <strong>Blac=
k Box Testing</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.White=
BoxTesting">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. White Box Testing</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Testing the <strong>internal structure and logic</strong> of the code. The =
tester must know the <strong>program=E2=80=99s internal details</strong>.</=
p>
<p><strong>Focus:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Control flow, loops, branches, conditions.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Coverage of statements, decisions, and paths.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Techniques:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Statement Coverage</strong> =E2=86=92 Ensure each line executes =
at least once.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Branch Coverage</strong> =E2=86=92 Ensure each decision outcome =
(true/false) executes.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Path Coverage</strong> =E2=86=92 Ensure all execution paths are =
tested.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example (Java):</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">int fin=
dMax(int a, int b, int c) {
    if(a &gt; b &amp;&amp; a &gt; c) return a;
    else if(b &gt; c) return b;
    else return c;
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=94 White Box Tests:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Case 1: <code>a</code> is largest (a=3D10, b=3D5, c=3D3).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Case 2: <code>b</code> is largest (a=3D3, b=3D8, c=3D4).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Case 3: <code>c</code> is largest (a=3D2, b=3D6, c=3D9).</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Here we ensure all <strong>branches</strong> are covered.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.Black=
BoxTesting">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. Black Box Testing</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Testing the <strong>functionality of software without knowing internal code=
</strong>. Focuses only on <strong>inputs and expected outputs</strong>.</p=
>
<p><strong>Techniques:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Equivalence Partitioning</strong> =E2=86=92 Divide input into va=
lid/invalid classes.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Boundary Value Analysis (BVA)</strong> =E2=86=92 Test values at =
boundaries (min, max, just inside/outside).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Cause-Effect Graphing</strong> =E2=86=92 Map conditions to outco=
mes.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
Suppose a system accepts an <strong>age between 18=E2=80=9360</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Equivalence classes:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>&lt; 18 (invalid)</p></li>
<li>
<p>18=E2=80=9360 (valid)</p></li>
<li>
<p>60 (invalid)</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Test Cases:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>17 (invalid), 18 (valid), 30 (valid), 60 (valid), 61 (invalid).</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 This ensures functional correctness without looking at code.</=
p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.Basis=
PathTesting(WhiteBoxMethod)">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Basis Path Testing (White Box =
Method)</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Technique for designing test cases using <strong>control flow graph (CFG)</=
strong> of the program.<br>
It ensures <strong>all independent paths</strong> are tested.</p>
<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Draw Control Flow Graph (CFG).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Compute <strong>Cyclomatic Complexity (V(G))</strong>:</p>
<p>V(G)=3DE=E2=88=92N+2V(G) =3D E - N + 2</p>
<p>(where E =3D edges, N =3D nodes).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Identify independent paths.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Design test cases for each path.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">if(x &g=
t; 0) {
   if(y &gt; 0) System.out.println("Quadrant I");
   else System.out.println("Quadrant IV");
} else {
   if(y &gt; 0) System.out.println("Quadrant II");
   else System.out.println("Quadrant III");
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Cyclomatic Complexity =3D 4</p></li>
<li>
<p>Independent Paths:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>x&gt;0, y&gt;0 =E2=86=92 Quadrant I</p></li>
<li>
<p>x&gt;0, y&lt;=3D0 =E2=86=92 Quadrant IV</p></li>
<li>
<p>x&lt;=3D0, y&gt;0 =E2=86=92 Quadrant II</p></li>
<li>
<p>x&lt;=3D0, y&lt;=3D0 =E2=86=92 Quadrant III</p></li>
</ol></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 We need at least 4 test cases.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.Testi=
ngforSpecializedEnvironments">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. Testing for Specialized Envir=
onments</h2>
<p>Some environments require <strong>specific testing techniques</strong> b=
eyond standard functional/non-functional testing.</p>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-Examples:">Examples=
:</h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Real-time Systems</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Must meet timing constraints.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Testing involves stress, load, and response-time analysis.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Distributed Systems</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Focus on network latency, synchronization, fault tolerance.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: Testing microservices communication via REST APIs.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Web Applications</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Test for security (SQL Injection, XSS), browser compatibility, session m=
anagement.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Mobile Applications</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Test on different devices, screen sizes, network conditions (2G, 3G, Wi-=
Fi).</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Embedded Systems</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Limited resources (CPU, memory).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Test under hardware constraints and real-world input signals.</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8E=AFSummary=
.1">=F0=9F=8E=AF Summary</h1>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>White Box Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Tests internal logic (branc=
h/path/statement coverage).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Black Box Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Tests input/output without =
knowing internal details (Equivalence Partitioning, BVA).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Basis Path Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Structured white-box testi=
ng using CFG and cyclomatic complexity.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Specialized Environment Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Tailored for =
real-time, distributed, web, mobile, and embedded systems.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Do you want me to also prepare <strong>example UML/Test cas=
e tables</strong> for White Box &amp; Black Box testing so you can use them=
 directly in exams or documentation?</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"11">
<li>
<p>Software testing strategies: Unit Testing, Integration Testing, Validati=
on Testing, System Testing, Art of debugging.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8C You asked about <strong>Software Testing Strategies=
</strong> =E2=86=92 this is the <strong>step-by-step testing approach</stro=
ng> used in Software Engineering. Let=E2=80=99s go one by one with <strong>=
definitions + examples in Java + debugging explanation</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=93=8CSoftwar=
eTestingStrategies">=F0=9F=93=8C Software Testing Strategies</h1>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.UnitT=
esting">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. Unit Testing</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Testing <strong>individual components (methods, classes, modules)</strong> =
of the software in isolation.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Focus: correctness of small units.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Usually automated using testing frameworks (JUnit in Java).</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example (Java JUnit test for a Calculator class):</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">class C=
alculator {
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}

import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class CalculatorTest {
    @Test
    public void testAdd() {
        Calculator calc =3D new Calculator();
        assertEquals(5, calc.add(2, 3));
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Tests only the <code>add()</code> function independently.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.Integ=
rationTesting">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. Integration Testing</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
After unit testing, we test <strong>how modules interact with each other</s=
trong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Ensures data flow between modules works correctly.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Strategies:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Big Bang</strong> =E2=86=92 integrate everything at once.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p><strong>Incremental</strong> =E2=86=92 integrate step by step (Top-down,=
 Bottom-up, Sandwich).</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>LoginService</code> (authenticates user)</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>DatabaseService</code> (fetches data)<br>
Integration test =E2=86=92 Verify login correctly pulls data from DB.</p></=
li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">public =
class IntegrationTest {
    @Test
    public void testLoginIntegration() {
        DatabaseService db =3D new DatabaseService();
        LoginService login =3D new LoginService(db);

        boolean result =3D login.authenticate("user", "password");
        assertTrue(result);
    }
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.Valid=
ationTesting">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Validation Testing</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Checks whether the <strong>final software meets the customer=E2=80=99s requ=
irements</strong> (Are we building the right product?).</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Based on <strong>Software Requirement Specification (SRS)</strong>.</p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>Usually <strong>Black Box Testing</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Requirement: =E2=80=9CSystem should not allow login with invalid passwor=
d.=E2=80=9D</p></li>
<li>
<p>Validation Test Case:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Input: username =3D "admin", password =3D "wrong"</p></li>
<li>
<p>Expected Output: "Invalid login message displayed."</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Confirms software behaves as per requirements.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.Syste=
mTesting">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. System Testing</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Testing the <strong>entire system as a whole</strong> after integration.</p=
>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Covers <strong>functional</strong> (features) and <strong>non-functional=
</strong> (performance, security, usability) aspects.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Done in an environment similar to production.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Load Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Many users at once.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Stress Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Extreme workload.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Security Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Authentication, SQL injectio=
n, etc.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Compatibility Testing</strong> =E2=86=92 Across browsers/devices=
.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong><br>
Testing an e-commerce system:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>User logs in =E2=86=92 searches product =E2=86=92 adds to cart =E2=86=92=
 makes payment.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Verify end-to-end workflow works properly.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B95.Artof=
Debugging">=F0=9F=94=B9 5. Art of Debugging</h2>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Debugging =3D <strong>Process of finding, analyzing, and fixing defects</st=
rong> discovered during testing.</p>
<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Reproduce the bug (using test case).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Identify the location (logs, breakpoints).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Analyze the root cause (logic, input errors, misconfiguration).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Fix the code.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Re-test to confirm.</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Common Debugging Techniques:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Print debugging</strong> =E2=86=92 using <code>System.out.printl=
n()</code> or logs.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Using Debugger tools</strong> (Eclipse/IntelliJ breakpoints, ste=
p execution).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Binary search debugging</strong> =E2=86=92 Narrow down faulty ar=
ea step by step.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example (Java):</strong></p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">public =
int divide(int a, int b) {
    return a / b;   // =E2=9D=8C Bug: no check for b=3D0
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Bug</strong>: Division by zero causes <code>ArithmeticException<=
/code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Fix</strong>:</p></li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">public =
int divide(int a, int b) {
    if (b =3D=3D 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Divider cannot be z=
ero");
    return a / b;
}
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Debugging ensures test failures are resolved.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8E=AFSummary=
Table">=F0=9F=8E=AF Summary Table</h1>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"8f=
f1ba41-e3f2-422d-abdd-a637fb9a7179" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Strategy</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Purpose</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Unit Testing</strong></p></td>
