<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Do you want me to also prepare a <strong>real project testi=
ng roadmap</strong> (which tests to do first, next, last) so you can see ho=
w these strategies connect in practice?</p>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8D Let=E2=80=99s build a <strong>real project testing =
roadmap</strong> that shows the <strong>order of testing strategies</strong=
> and how they connect in practice.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=9A=80RealPro=
jectTestingRoadmap">=F0=9F=9A=80 Real Project Testing Roadmap</h1>
<p>Imagine we are building an <strong>E-commerce Web Application</strong> (=
Login =E2=86=92 Browse Products =E2=86=92 Add to Cart =E2=86=92 Checkout =
=E2=86=92 Payment).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Step1:U=
nitTesting(Firstlayer)">=F0=9F=94=B9 Step 1: Unit Testing (First layer)</h2=
>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Verify small pieces of code (methods/classes).</p=
>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example Tests:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>UserService.login()</code> =E2=86=92 Returns true for valid creden=
tials.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>Cart.addProduct()</code> =E2=86=92 Adds product correctly.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p><code>Payment.calculateTotal()</code> =E2=86=92 Returns correct sum.</p>=
</li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C Tool in Java =E2=86=92 <strong>JUnit + Mockito (for mocking=
 dependencies)</strong></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Step2:I=
ntegrationTesting(Secondlayer)">=F0=9F=94=B9 Step 2: Integration Testing (S=
econd layer)</h2>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Verify modules work together correctly.</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example Tests:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>LoginService</code> =E2=86=94 <code>DatabaseService</code> =E2=86=
=92 User fetched correctly.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>CartService</code> =E2=86=94 <code>InventoryService</code> =E2=86=
=92 Stock decreases after adding to cart.</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>OrderService</code> =E2=86=94 <code>PaymentGateway</code> =E2=86=
=92 Payment processed successfully.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C Tool in Java =E2=86=92 <strong>JUnit + Spring Boot Test (if=
 using Spring)</strong></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Step3:V=
alidationTesting(Thirdlayer)">=F0=9F=94=B9 Step 3: Validation Testing (Thir=
d layer)</h2>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Check system against <strong>requirements (SRS)</=
strong>.</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example Test Cases:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Invalid login should not allow access.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Checkout must not proceed if cart is empty.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Discount coupon should reduce price correctly.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C Tool =E2=86=92 Manual functional testing + automated accept=
ance tests (<strong>Cucumber for BDD</strong>).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Step4:S=
ystemTesting(Fourthlayer)">=F0=9F=94=B9 Step 4: System Testing (Fourth laye=
r)</h2>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Test the full application in a near-production en=
vironment.</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Types of System Tests:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Functional</strong> =E2=86=92 End-to-end user flow (login =E2=86=
=92 add to cart =E2=86=92 payment).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Performance/Load</strong> =E2=86=92 500 users checkout at the sa=
me time.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Security</strong> =E2=86=92 SQL injection prevention, secure pay=
ment API.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Compatibility</strong> =E2=86=92 Works in Chrome, Firefox, mobil=
e browsers.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C Tools =E2=86=92 <strong>Selenium (UI Automation), JMeter (P=
erformance), OWASP ZAP (Security).</strong></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Step5:D=
ebugging(Ongoingatallstages)">=F0=9F=94=B9 Step 5: Debugging (Ongoing at al=
l stages)</h2>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Find and fix errors quickly when tests fail.</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example Debugging Steps:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Unit test fails =E2=86=92 check function logic.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Integration test fails =E2=86=92 check API calls/logs.</p></li>
<li>
<p>System test fails =E2=86=92 check configuration, environment issues.</p>=
</li>
</ol>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C Tools =E2=86=92 <strong>IntelliJ/Eclipse Debugger, Logging =
(Log4j/SLF4J), Postman for API debugging.</strong></p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8F=97=EF=B8=
=8FTestingRoadmapasaPyramid">=F0=9F=8F=97=EF=B8=8F Testing Roadmap as a Pyr=
amid</h1>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">       =
  [ System Testing ]      =E2=86=90 End-to-end workflows, security, perform=
ance
        [ Validation Testing ]   =E2=86=90 Meets customer requirements
       [ Integration Testing ]   =E2=86=90 Module interactions tested
      [ Unit Testing ]           =E2=86=90 Smallest components tested
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Debugging happens <strong>at every level</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8E=AFFinalNo=
tesforaRealProject">=F0=9F=8E=AF Final Notes for a Real Project</h1>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Start small (Unit) =E2=86=92 Build upward (Integration, Validati=
on, System).</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Automate <strong>Unit + Integration tests</strong>, but keep <strong>Sys=
tem tests</strong> partially manual (with automation for regression).</p></=
li>
<li>
<p>Always follow the <strong>Testing Pyramid</strong> =E2=86=92 More unit t=
ests, fewer system tests (cost/time efficiency).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>Would you like me to also create a <strong>sample test plan document</st=
rong> (with objectives, scope, strategy, tools, and deliverables) for this =
e-commerce system so you can see how testing is formally planned in the ind=
ustry?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"12">
<li>
<p>Analysis of System Maintenance and upgrading: Software repair, downtime,=
 error and faults, specification and correction, Maintenance cost models, d=
ocumentation.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Great question =F0=9F=91=8D Let=E2=80=99s go through <strong>System Main=
tenance and Upgrading</strong> in <strong>Software Engineering</strong> ste=
p by step with clear explanations, examples, and industry practices.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=A7SystemM=
aintenanceandUpgrading">=F0=9F=94=A7 <strong>System Maintenance and Upgradi=
ng</strong></h1>
<p>After a system is deployed, it requires continuous support to <strong>fi=
x problems, improve performance, adapt to new environments, and enhance fea=
tures</strong>. This stage is often the <strong>most expensive part of the =
software lifecycle</strong> (sometimes &gt;60% of total cost).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.Softw=
areRepair">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. Software Repair</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Fixing defects or errors discovered after deployment.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Ensures system continues to function as expected.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A banking app crashes when processing large transactions =E2=86=92 Patch=
 released to fix memory leak.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.Downt=
ime">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. Downtime</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Time when the system is <strong>unavailable due to maintenance or failur=
es</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Can be <strong>planned</strong> (e.g., upgrades, server migration) or <s=
trong>unplanned</strong> (system crashes).</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>An e-commerce site schedules downtime from 2 AM =E2=80=93 4 AM for syste=
m updates.</p></li>
<li>
<p>If downtime is unplanned (server crash during Black Friday sale), it can=
 cause <strong>huge losses</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.Error=
sandFaults">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Errors and Faults</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Error</strong> =E2=86=92 Human mistake (e.g., wrong formula code=
d).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Fault (Bug/Defect)</strong> =E2=86=92 The incorrect part in the =
software code/design.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Failure</strong> =E2=86=92 When the software <strong>does not pe=
rform as required</strong> in execution.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Error =E2=86=92 Developer forgets to check for null values.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Fault =E2=86=92 Null pointer bug in the code.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Failure =E2=86=92 Application crashes when user logs in with null input.=
</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.Speci=
ficationandCorrection">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. Specification and Correction</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Sometimes requirements change after deployment =E2=86=92 Software must b=
e updated to match new specifications.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Correction involves <strong>fixing defects and ensuring compliance</stro=
ng> with updated requirements.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Govt. changes tax calculation rules =E2=86=92 ERP system specification u=
pdated =E2=86=92 Developer corrects formulas.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B95.Maint=
enanceCostModels">=F0=9F=94=B9 5. Maintenance Cost Models</h2>
<p>Software maintenance is costly because it involves <strong>analysis, tes=
ting, regression checks, and deployment</strong>.</p>
<p>Types of maintenance (IEEE Standard):</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"05=
6847ac-8c22-47ba-984e-1c3c2d4fca2d" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p><strong>Type</strong></p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p><strong>Definition</strong></p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p><strong>Example</strong></p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Corrective</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Fixing bugs/errors</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Fix login issue</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Adaptive</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Modifying software for new environment</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Update app for Android 15</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Perfective</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Improving performance or features</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Optimize search speed</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Preventive</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Future-proofing, reducing risks</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Refactor old code, security patches</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C <strong>Cost Models:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Bohem=E2=80=99s Model</strong>: Cost of maintenance increases wi=
th time (older systems are harder to maintain).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Lehman=E2=80=99s Law</strong>: "Software must continually evolve=
 or become obsolete."</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Percentage rule</strong>: 60=E2=80=9380% of software lifecycle c=
ost is maintenance.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B96.Docum=
entation">=F0=9F=94=B9 6. Documentation</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Essential for efficient maintenance.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Includes <strong>requirements, design docs, test cases, user manuals, AP=
I docs, change logs</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Without documentation, debugging/upgrades become <strong>very costly</st=
rong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>If a developer leaves the company, proper documentation ensures new deve=
lopers can maintain the system without re-learning everything.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8F=97=EF=B8=
=8FSummaryDiagram">=F0=9F=8F=97=EF=B8=8F Summary Diagram</h1>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">System =
Maintenance
 =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80=E2=94=80 Software Repair
 =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80=E2=94=80 Downtime
 =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80=E2=94=80 Errors &amp; Faults
 =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80=E2=94=80 Specification &amp; Correction
 =E2=94=9C=E2=94=80=E2=94=80 Maintenance Cost Models
 =E2=94=94=E2=94=80=E2=94=80 Documentation
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8E=AFKeyIndu=
stryInsight">=F0=9F=8E=AF Key Industry Insight</h1>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Companies reduce downtime with <strong>CI/CD pipelines</strong> (continu=
ous deployment with rolling updates).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Use <strong>Monitoring Tools</strong> (Prometheus, Grafana, Splunk) to d=
etect failures early.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Automated regression testing</strong> is a must before upgrades.=
</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>Would you like me to also create a <strong>real-world case study example=
</strong> (like how Google or Amazon handles downtime &amp; maintenance) so=
 it=E2=80=99s easier to connect theory with practice?</p>
<p>Perfect =E2=9C=85 Let=E2=80=99s go through a <strong>real-world case stu=
dy</strong> on how big companies like <strong>Google</strong> and <strong>A=
mazon</strong> handle <strong>software maintenance, downtime, and upgrades<=
/strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=8F=A2CaseStu=
dy1:Google(Gmail&amp;YouTube)">=F0=9F=8F=A2 <strong>Case Study 1: Google (G=
mail &amp; YouTube)</strong></h1>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.Softw=
areRepair.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. Software Repair</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>When Gmail had a <strong>major outage in 2019</strong> due to backend st=
orage issues, Google=E2=80=99s engineers quickly identified the <strong>fau=
lty server cluster</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>A <strong>patch</strong> was deployed across data centers worldwide.</p>=
</li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Rapid patch deployment</strong> and <=
strong>root cause analysis (RCA)</strong> are critical.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.Downt=
imeHandling">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. Downtime Handling</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Google avoids <strong>global downtime</strong> by using <strong>distribu=
ted data centers</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>If one region fails, traffic is rerouted to another =E2=86=92 <strong>Ze=
ro planned downtime</strong> for users.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Updates are deployed <strong>incrementally</strong> =E2=86=92 new featur=
es roll out to <strong>1% of users first</strong>, then expand.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Rolling updates + regional failover =
=3D minimal downtime</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.Error=
s,Faults,Failures">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Errors, Faults, Failures</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Example: YouTube video playback issues in 2020 were caused by a <strong>=
fault in the CDN (Content Delivery Network)</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Failure occurred only in <strong>high traffic regions</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Google used <strong>automated monitoring + error logging</strong> to det=
ect and rollback faulty configs.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Monitor, Detect, Rollback quickly</st=
rong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.Speci=
fication&amp;Correction">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. Specification &amp; Correction</h3=
>
<ul>
<li>
<p>New privacy laws (e.g., <strong>GDPR in Europe</strong>) required Google=
 to <strong>update Gmail &amp; YouTube data retention policies</strong>.</p=
></li>
<li>
<p>Engineers had to <strong>modify database schemas</strong> and update <st=
rong>user consent features</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Regulation-driven changes require fas=
t adaptation</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B95.Maint=
enanceCost">=F0=9F=94=B9 5. Maintenance Cost</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Google spends <strong>billions annually</strong> on maintaining and upgr=
ading cloud/software infrastructure.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Most cost goes to <strong>adaptive and perfective maintenance</strong> (=
supporting new platforms, improving performance).</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Maintenance is more expensive than in=
itial development</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=9B=92CaseStu=
dy2:Amazon(E-Commerce+AWS)">=F0=9F=9B=92 <strong>Case Study 2: Amazon (E-Co=
mmerce + AWS)</strong></h1>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B91.Softw=
areRepair.2">=F0=9F=94=B9 1. Software Repair</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>In 2021, Amazon Web Services (AWS) had a <strong>major outage</strong> d=
ue to <strong>misconfigured traffic routing</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Engineers quickly <strong>isolated faulty components</strong> and applie=
d hotfixes.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Fault isolation =3D faster recovery</=
strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B92.Downt=
imeHandling.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 2. Downtime Handling</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Amazon uses <strong>Blue-Green Deployment</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Blue =3D Current version</p></li>
<li>
<p>Green =3D New version</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>If Green fails =E2=86=92 instantly rollback to Blue (zero downtime for c=
ustomers).</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example =E2=86=92 Updating checkout system during Black Friday=
 without downtime.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B93.Error=
s,Faults,Failures.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 3. Errors, Faults, Failures</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Amazon constantly runs <strong>Chaos Engineering</strong> experiments (l=
ike Netflix=E2=80=99s Chaos Monkey).</p></li>
<li>
<p>They <strong>intentionally shut down servers</strong> to see if the syst=
em still works.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Prepare for failures BEFORE they happ=
en</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B94.Speci=
fication&amp;Correction.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 4. Specification &amp; Correction</=
h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Amazon Pay needed <strong>integration with new RBI (India) regulations</=
strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Engineers updated <strong>APIs, authentication flows, and transaction li=
mits</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Lesson =E2=86=92 <strong>Market-driven regulatory changes dema=
nd frequent corrections</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B95.Docum=
entation">=F0=9F=94=B9 5. Documentation</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Amazon enforces <strong>strict documentation</strong> =E2=86=92 every sy=
stem change must include:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Design Doc</p></li>
<li>
<p>Test Cases</p></li>
<li>
<p>Rollback Plan</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p>Without documentation, new engineers would not be able to handle critica=
l services like <strong>Prime Day traffic surge</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=91Industr=
yTakeaways">=F0=9F=94=91 <strong>Industry Takeaways</strong></h1>
<p>=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F <strong>Google</strong> =E2=86=92 Focuses on distribu=
ted, fault-tolerant systems =E2=86=92 No single point of failure.<br>
=E2=9C=94=EF=B8=8F <strong>Amazon</strong> =E2=86=92 Focuses on continuous =
delivery &amp; rollback =E2=86=92 No downtime during updates.</p>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8C Both companies invest heavily in:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Automated testing &amp; monitoring</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Rolling/Blue-Green deployments</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Chaos testing &amp; resilience engineering</strong></p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9A=A1 Quick Visual (Maintenance Lifecycle in Industry):</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">Bug Fou=
nd =E2=86=92 Patch =E2=86=92 Regression Testing =E2=86=92 Deploy (Blue-Gree=
n / Rolling)=20
=E2=86=92 Monitor =E2=86=92 If Fail =E2=86=92 Rollback =E2=86=92 Document F=
ix
</pre>
</div>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Do you want me to also prepare a <strong>comparison table o=
f Maintenance Strategies</strong> (Google vs Amazon vs Traditional Software=
 Companies) so you can use it for exams/interviews easily?</p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"13">
<li>
<p>Software Quality Assurance, Quality factors.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Software quality measures.</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Got it =F0=9F=91=8D Let=E2=80=99s go step by step like a <strong>Softwar=
e Engineer</strong> explaining to juniors:</p>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Softwar=
eQualityAssurance(SQA)">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>Software Quality Assurance (SQ=
A)</strong></h1>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 <strong>Definition</strong>:<br>
Software Quality Assurance is a <strong>set of activities</strong> that ens=
ure the software being developed <strong>meets the required quality standar=
ds</strong>.<br>
It covers <strong>the entire software development lifecycle (SDLC)</strong>=
, not just testing.</p>
<p>=F0=9F=94=91 <strong>Key Goals of SQA</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Ensure the software is <strong>reliable, secure, and maintainable</stron=
g>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Prevent <strong>defects</strong> rather than just detecting them.</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>Comply with <strong>standards</strong> (e.g., ISO 9001, CMMI, IEEE).</p>=
</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Softwar=
eQualityFactors">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>Software Quality Factors</strong></h1=
>
<p>McCall=E2=80=99s Quality Model (classic model used in SQA) defines softw=
are quality based on <strong>factors</strong>:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"c3=
003de3-920c-48e4-882e-7cae4c7c3448" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p><strong>Category</strong></p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p><strong>Quality Factor</strong></p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p><strong>Meaning</strong></p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Product Operation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Correctness</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Software does what it is supposed to do.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Reliability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Works consistently without failure.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Efficiency</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Uses resources (CPU, memory, network) optimally.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Integrity</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Secure against unauthorized access.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Usability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Easy to use and learn.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Product Revision</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Maintainability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Easy to fix bugs and update.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Flexibility</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Easy to modify for new requirements.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Testability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Easy to test with automated/manual testing.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Product Transition</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Portability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Can run on different platforms easily.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Reusability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Code/components can be reused.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Interoperability</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Works with other systems.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Example:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>WhatsApp</strong> =E2=86=92 high <em>usability</em>, <em>reliabi=
lity</em>, <em>interoperability</em>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Banking Software</strong> =E2=86=92 must ensure <em>correctness<=
/em>, <em>integrity</em>, <em>security</em>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Softwar=
eQualityMeasures(Metrics)">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>Software Quality Measures (=
Metrics)</strong></h1>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Metrics =3D Quantitative way to measure software quality.</=
p>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-1.ProductMetrics(Ab=
outthesoftwareitself)">1. <strong>Product Metrics</strong> (About the softw=
are itself)</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Defect Density</strong> =3D (No. of defects) / (Size of software=
 in KLOC/FP)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Reliability</strong> =3D MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures)</p></=
li>
<li>
<p><strong>Usability Score</strong> =3D User feedback / surveys</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-2.ProcessMetrics(Ab=
outtheSDLCprocess)">2. <strong>Process Metrics</strong> (About the SDLC pro=
cess)</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Defect Removal Efficiency (DRE)</strong> =3D</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: java; gutter: false; theme: Confluence" data-theme=3D"Confluence">DRE =3D=
 Defects found before release / (Defects before + after release)
</pre>
</div>
</div></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Effort Variance</strong> =3D (Planned Effort =E2=80=93 Actual Ef=
fort) / Planned Effort</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-3.ProjectMetrics(Ab=
outoverallprojecthealth)">3. <strong>Project Metrics</strong> (About overal=
l project health)</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Schedule Variance (SV)</strong> =3D Planned time =E2=80=93 Actua=
l time</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Cost Variance (CV)</strong> =3D Planned cost =E2=80=93 Actual co=
st</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 id=3D"SoftwareEngineeringandInformationSystemDesign-=F0=9F=94=B9Example=
(Real-WorldQualityMeasures)">=F0=9F=94=B9 Example (Real-World Quality Measu=
res)</h1>
<p>Suppose you are developing a <strong>Banking App</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Correctness</strong> =E2=86=92 Does the app calculate interest c=
orrectly?</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Reliability</strong> =E2=86=92 Does it work without crashing dur=
ing peak hours?</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Efficiency</strong> =E2=86=92 How much memory and CPU does it us=
e?</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Integrity</strong> =E2=86=92 Is user data secure (encrypted)?</p=
></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Usability</strong> =E2=86=92 Can a non-technical user transfer m=
oney easily?</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=91=89 Metrics applied:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Defect Density =3D 5 defects / 1000 LOC =3D <strong>0.005</strong></p></=
li>
<li>
<p>DRE =3D 90% (means most bugs were caught before release).</p></li>
<li>
<p>MTBF =3D 200 hours (system fails once every ~200 hours).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In summary</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>SQA</strong> =3D preventive + monitoring activities across SDLC.=
</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Quality Factors</strong> =3D attributes like reliability, usabil=
ity, maintainability.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Quality Measures</strong> =3D metrics (defect density, MTBF, DRE=
, CV, SV) to track &amp; improve quality.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
